Caesalpinia bonduc

(L.) Roxb. (
Fabaceae
) is a stout prickly climber widely distributed in Southeast Asia and other tropical regions of the world (

). Its seeds have been used in Chinese folk medicine to treat common cold and dysentery (

), and also have the function of promoting blood circulation to arrest pain, and removing toxicity for detumescence (Editorial 

). In Indian, various parts of this plant are used to treat cough, fever, headache, and stomach problems (

). The extract of this plant has been proved to exhibit antitumor, antibacterial, anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and antidiabetic effects (

). Furthermore, a wide variety of cassane diterpenes have been isolated from 

C. bonduc

and have been reported to possess significant antiproliferative (

, 

), antimalarial (

), and anthelmintic (

) activities. In a continuing search for bioactive cassane-type diterpenoids from 

Caesalpinia
species

(

; 

), a 95% EtOH extract of the seeds of 

C. bonduc

were investigated, which resulted in the isolation of previously undescribed ten diterpenoids, caesalbonducins A-J (
1–10
), as well as eleven known ones (
Fig. 1
). Herein, we describe the isolation, structural elucidation, and nitric oxide (NO) and 
α
-glucosidase inhibitory activities of the isolated compounds.

A 95% EtOH extract of the air-dried seeds of 

C. bonduc

was partitioned between H 
2
O and EtOAc. The EtOAc fraction was subjected to MCI gel, silica gel, Sephadex LH-20, and semipreparative HPLC to afford ten previously undescribed cassane diterpenoids, cassabonducins A-J (
1–10
), as well as eleven known compounds (
11–21
