The extract of this plant has been proved to have anti-inflammatory and antidiabetic effects (
). In addition, some cassane diterpenoids have been reported to possess potent anti-inflammatory activity (
;
,
). So, compounds 1–21 were evaluated for their nitric oxide (NO) production and α- glucosidase inhibitory activities. Compound 1 was found to exhibit potent inhibitory activity against LPS-induced NO production in RAW 264.7 macrophages with IC 50 value of 6.12 μ M, compared to 45.36 μ M of L-NMMA ( N G- Monomethyl-L-arginine). The other compounds were inactive (IC 50 > 50 μM). Compounds 4 and 17 exhibited moderate α -glucosidase inhibition at 50 μ M with inhibitory rates of 47.17% and 43.83%, respectively, compared to the inhibitory rate of 58.71% for quercetin at 10 μM. The other compounds were inactive with inhibitory rate of lower than 30%.

The ECD calculations of 
